{
  "texts": [
    "Representative/diversity-based algorithms include a multitude of approaches that are commonly classified in two main schemes: clustering methodology and optimal experimental design.",
    "The former clustering algorithms identifies the most representative locations exploiting the underlying structures of the domain: the utility of samples is obtained as a function of their distance from the cluster centers.",
    "Popular examples include hierarchical clustering and k-center clustering.",
    "The former identifies a hierarchy of clusters based on the encoded information, and selects samples closer to the cluster centers [18]; the latter determines a subset of k congruent clusters that together cover the sampling space and whose radius is minimized, and the best sample minimizes the maximum distance of any point to a center [117].",
    "The latter optimal experimental design defines a sampling policy based on a transductive approach: the learning procedure conducts the queries through a data reconstruction framework that measure the samples representativeness based on the capacity to reconstruct the training dataset."
  ]
}